@jaraco I think one thing about putting them under version guards is that you'll naturally see when they've "aged out" because once you stop testing against a version, the coverage under that guard will go to zero and they can just be safely deleted.

If you have to specify which specific module they come from, then you have to dig it out of more files. Still, I do think it's a reasonable enough approach - since that *will* allow you to quickly find all the files that are using functions from `pyXYcompat` and remove the shim *entirely*.

Maybe all the `py31compat` stuff that still applies to Python 2.7 should be moved into `py27compat.py`, and the rest should be deleted?

