I'm not sure if your code (the first part) is right or not, it's too complicated for me to hold in my head. You could argue that it's correct, and as a proof point to the tests.  In general I try to avoid writing code that tests more than one thing at a time, unless it's very clear what's going on. In this situation we have various things that may or may not be the case: `matchAmbiguous` might be True/False, and the bases involved might be identical but not ambiguous, non-identical but a match if we're allowing ambiguous matches, etc.   I guess there might be 8 (2^3) cases, but your code only has 4 possible things that it does. So the reader has to try to understand the code and simultaneously try to think whether those 4 outcomes handle the 8 possible scenarios properly. It's too hard, at least for my brain.  So I'd probably do this:

```python
if matchAmbiguous:
    if a == b:
        if len(AMBIGUOUS[a]) == 1:
            identicalMatchCount += 1
        else:
            ambiguousMatchCount += 1
    else:
        if AMBIGUOUS.get(a, empty) & AMBIGUOUS.get(b, empty):
            ambiguousMatchCount += 1
        else:
            nonGapMismatchCount += 1
else:
    if a == b and len(AMBIGUOUS[a]) == 1:
        identicalMatchCount += 1
    else:
        nonGapMismatchCount += 1
```

You can see I've made an exception to my just-test-one-thing-at-a-time guideline in the final if, where I have `if a == b and len(AMBIGUOUS[a]) == 1` but that part is quite clear (to me).  You can also see from the code that there are 3 levels of tests and so as a reader you're expecting 8 different possible treatments. But you count them and see that there are only 6. It's very clear from the structure of the code that 4 cases/outcomes appear in the upper half but there are only 2 actions in the bottom half. But you can see that the first part in the bottom (`if a == b and len(AMBIGUOUS[a]) == 1`) is treating 1 of the 4 possibilities and that `nonGapMismatchCount += 1` covers the other 3.

It's all a bit down to taste and experience. For me the above is below the threshold where I start to get confused, so it's ok. Another plus from writing your code like that is that it's very easy to comment it with short definitive statements (like `# Neither is a gap character.` that can really help the reader (who is probably you, or will be you)).

If you want to be super explicit, you can not collapse that final `if`, so you'd have:

```python
if matchAmbiguous:
    if a == b:
        if len(AMBIGUOUS[a]) == 1:
            identicalMatchCount += 1
        else:
            ambiguousMatchCount += 1
    else:
        if AMBIGUOUS.get(a, empty) & AMBIGUOUS.get(b, empty):
            ambiguousMatchCount += 1
        else:
            nonGapMismatchCount += 1
else:
    if a == b:
        if len(AMBIGUOUS[a]) == 1:
            identicalMatchCount += 1
        else:
            nonGapMismatchCount += 1
    else:
        if len(AMBIGUOUS[a]) == 1:
            nonGapMismatchCount += 1
        else:
            nonGapMismatchCount += 1
```

But that's getting repetitive and is also a bit weird since in the final part we know `a !=b` but we only examine `len(AMBIGUOUS[a])` which looks wrong.  So that's why I collapsed those 3 `nonGapMismatchCount += 1` cases into one in the earlier code.

Also, as a way of writing this kind of code, it's good to first write it out in the most verbose / expanded form (all cases treated) and only then try to collapse some with equivalent outcomes, as long as that doesn't make the code harder to understand.  Understandable code is the most important thing, arguably more important than it being correct :-)

Anyway, I try to be humble and not too dictatorial about these things. Even after 40 years of programming I still make errors like the one we're now trying to understand / fix.

Sometimes there are more than 3 levels of logic, too :-)

