The method `ray.get_gpu_ids` is meant to be used inside of tasks and actors, so that GPUs can be allocated to tasks and actors.

For example, it is intended to work as follows.

```python
@ray.actor(num_gpus=1)
class Foo(object):
  def __init__(self):
    gpu_ids = ray.get_gpu_ids()
```

The following will also work after #403 is merged.

```python
@ray.remote(num_gpus=1)
def f():
  ray.get_gpu_ids()
```

The intended use case is that the local scheduler can assign different GPUs on a node to different tasks or actors that use GPUs. Note that for this to work, you have to start Ray with `ray.init(num_gpus=4)` or something like that.

Currently it is not possible to assign a GPU to the driver process, though I could see that being useful.

